    <refsection id="Description_TrigFun">
        <title>Description</title>
        <para>
            The Trigonometric Function block performs numerous common trigonometric functions. You can select a function
            among those quoted in this table :
        </para>
        <para/>
        <informaltable border="1" cellpadding="2">
            <tr>
                <td align="left">
                    <emphasis role="bold">Function</emphasis>
                </td>
                <td align="left">
                    <emphasis role="bold">Definition</emphasis>
                </td>
                <td align="left">
                    <emphasis role="bold">Output</emphasis>
                </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td align="left">sin</td>
                <td align="left">Sine of the input (radians)</td>
                <td align="left">y = sin(u)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td align="left">cos</td>
                <td align="left">Cosine of the input (radians)</td>
                <td align="left">y = cos(u)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td align="left">tan</td>
                <td align="left">Tangent of the input (radians)</td>
                <td align="left">y = tan(u)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td align="left">asin</td>
                <td align="left">Inverse sine (radians) of the input</td>
                <td align="left">y = asin(u)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td align="left">acos</td>
                <td align="left">Inverse cosine (radians) of the input</td>
                <td align="left">y = acos(u)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td align="left">atan</td>
                <td align="left">2-quadrant and 4-quadrant inverse tangent (radians) of the input</td>
                <td align="left">y = atan(u)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td align="left">sinh</td>
                <td align="left">Hyperbolic sine of the input</td>
                <td align="left">y = sinh(u)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td align="left">cosh</td>
                <td align="left">Hyperbolic cosine of the input</td>
                <td align="left">y = cosh(u)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td align="left">tanh</td>
                <td align="left">Hyperbolic tangent of the input</td>
                <td align="left">y = tanh(u)</td>
            </tr>
        </informaltable>
        <para>
            The block output is the result of the applied function on the scalar input or on the vector's elements of input.
        </para>
    </refsection>
